FINDINGS SUMMARY (Pre-Visualization)
Research Question: How do Lojano vs. non-Lojano listeners evaluate
trilled vs. assibilated speakers, and does this differ by region?


STUDY CONTEXT

All 8 speakers are natives of Loja, Ecuador (highland variety). The trill
is the normative/prestige form in Loja (García 2019; Gómez 2022), while
assibilation is the stigmatized form associated with indigenous populations
and lower education (Toapanta 2016; Gómez 2022). The dataset includes 210
unique respondents and 1619 observations (after pivot) from 4 listener
regions: Coast, Cuenca, Loja, and Quito. All attitude variables were rated
on 1-6 scales; masculinity was computed as 7 - fem (ClaraDraft.R line 147),
and status was computed as rowMeans of scaled class, urban, and edu
(lines 172, 216).


SECTION 1: FACTOR ANALYSIS (lines 160-172)

factanal() with varimax rotation and 2 factors was run on the variables
masculinity, nice, class, urban, edu, and age.

Factor 1 is Status. Class, urban, and edu loaded heavily together, forming
a single latent social prestige dimension. Listeners do not evaluate class,
urbanness, and education independently — when a speaker sounds high class,
they also sound urban and educated. This replicates García (2019), who found
the same unified status factor using the same listener population and speaker
corpus from Loja.

Factor 2 is Gendered Affect. Masculinity loaded negatively and nice loaded
positively, reflecting a classic gender-personality trade-off in
sociolinguistic perception: speakers heard as more dominant or masculine are
rated as less warm. Age did not load strongly on either factor.

The status composite variable (lines 172, 216) is both statistically and
theoretically justified by the factor analysis and is used as a predictor
and outcome in all subsequent regression models.


SECTION 2: TRILL AND STATUS — BIDIRECTIONAL LINK
trillmod1 (line 231), statusmod (line 248)

trillmod1 modeled trill as the outcome with status as the fixed effect. The
status estimate was 0.1192 (z = 1.999, p = 0.046), giving an odds ratio of
approximately 1.126. A 1-unit increase in perceived status increases the
odds of perceiving a trill by about 12.6%.

statusmod flipped the direction, modeling status as the outcome with trill
as the fixed effect. The trill estimate was 0.0848 (t = 2.641, significant
at |t| > 2), meaning hearing a trilled speaker raises perceived status by
0.085 units on the composite scale, independent of listener and speaker
variability.

The trill and social prestige are bidirectionally linked in perception.
Trilled speakers are rated as higher status, and higher-status speakers are
more likely to be perceived as trilling. This is consistent with the
normative prestige of the trill in Lojano Spanish specifically, where it
is the standard, educated form (Toscano Mateus 1953; García 2019).


SECTION 3: TRILL BY REGION ON STATUS ATTITUDES
statusmod_int: status ~ trill * Region + (1|RespondentID) + (1|speakerID)

None of the trill by Region interactions were significant for status
ratings. The main effect of trill was also non-significant when region
interactions were included (t = 0.148). All 95% Wald confidence intervals
for the interaction terms included zero.

The effect of trill on perceived status does not differ meaningfully between
Loja listeners and non-Loja listeners, or between any of the four regions.
The status-boosting effect of the trill documented in statusmod (line 248)
is uniform across listener regions. The prestige indexing of the trill is
not a local in-group phenomenon — it is shared across Ecuador's regional
listener groups.

The attitude_by_region summary table shows a consistent positive trill-status
gap across all regions: Coast (+0.004), Cuenca (+0.111), Loja (+0.085), and
Quito (+0.134). Quito and Cuenca listeners show the largest numerical status
boost for trilled speakers, though none of the interactions reached
statistical significance.


SECTION 4: TRILL BY REGION ON NICENESS ATTITUDES
nicemod_int: nice ~ trill * Region + (1|RespondentID) + (1|speakerID)

No trill by Region interactions were significant for niceness ratings. The
main effect of trill on niceness was also non-significant (t = 0.718). The
only significant effect in this model was RegionCuenca as a main effect
(t = -2.561, p < 0.05): Cuenca-region listeners give lower niceness ratings
overall regardless of trill condition. This is a listener baseline
difference, not a trill-specific evaluation.

This is consistent with nicemod (line 253), which showed trill had no direct
effect on niceness once status was controlled. No region evaluates trilled
speakers as warmer than assibilated speakers independently of status.

Mean niceness by region and trill condition from attitude_by_region:
Coast trill=0: 4.29, trill=1: 4.36
Cuenca trill=0: 3.86, trill=1: 3.94
Loja trill=0: 4.20, trill=1: 4.20
Quito trill=0: 4.28, trill=1: 4.26

Notably, Loja listeners give identical niceness ratings (4.20) to both
trilled and assibilated speakers. The in-group shows no warmth premium for
the normative trill form — it is simply expected.


SECTION 5: TRILL BY REGION ON MASCULINITY ATTITUDES
mascmod_int: masculinity ~ trill * Region + (1|RespondentID) + (1|speakerID)

No significant effects were found — neither trill, region, nor their
interaction predicted masculinity ratings. All 95% Wald confidence intervals
spanned zero for all terms.

This is consistent with mascmod (line 257), where trill was non-significant
once status was controlled (t = 1.086). Masculinity perception is driven by
status (t = -14.510 in mascmod) rather than by trill condition or listener
regional identity. Higher-status speakers are rated as less masculine,
reflecting the Factor 2 Gendered Affect dimension from the factor analysis.

Mean masculinity by region and trill condition from attitude_by_region:
Coast trill=0: 2.45, trill=1: 2.44
Cuenca trill=0: 2.65, trill=1: 2.72
Loja trill=0: 2.59, trill=1: 2.53
Quito trill=0: 2.38, trill=1: 2.46

Differences are negligible. No region consistently rates trilled speakers
as more or less masculine.


SECTION 6: CORRECT LOJA IDENTIFICATION
lojamod (main effects), lojamod_int (trill by Region interaction)

lojamod: guessed_loja ~ trill + status + Gender + Region
          + (1|RespondentID) + (1|speakerID)

drop1() likelihood ratio test results:
trill: LRT = 21.78, p = 3.05e-06 ***
status: LRT = 14.77, p = 0.000121 ***
Gender: LRT = 1.02, p = 0.313 (ns)
Region: LRT = 27.35, p = 4.97e-06 ***

Key fixed effects and odds ratios:
trill: estimate = 0.5473 (z = 4.674, p = 2.95e-06), OR = 1.729
  95% CI: 1.374 to 2.175
status: estimate = 0.3166 (z = 3.866, p = 0.000111), OR = 1.373
  95% CI: 1.169 to 1.611
RegionLoja: estimate = 0.9494 (z = 3.682, p = 0.000232), OR = 2.584
  95% CI: 1.559 to 4.284
RegionQuito: estimate = 0.6090 (z = 2.016, p = 0.044), OR = 1.839
  95% CI: 1.017 to 3.324
RegionCuenca: estimate = -0.2402 (z = -0.839, p = 0.401), ns

The trill is the strongest phonetic predictor of correct Loja attribution.
Hearing a trilled speaker nearly doubles the odds of correctly identifying
that speaker as Lojano (OR = 1.729, p = 2.95e-06). This is the headline
finding: the trill functions as an acoustic marker that helps listeners
place speakers in Loja, the only highland variety where the trill is
strongly normative (García 2019).

Status also significantly predicts correct attribution (OR = 1.373):
higher-status-sounding speakers are more likely to be identified as Lojano,
consistent with Loja's reputation as the most correct highland variety
(Toscano Mateus 1953).

Loja listeners are 2.584 times more likely to correctly identify Lojano
speakers than Coast listeners (the reference), p = 0.000232. Quito
listeners also show a marginal advantage (OR = 1.839, p = 0.044). Cuenca
listeners do not differ significantly from Coast listeners. This in-group
advantage is consistent with García (2019) Figure 6 and with Clopper and
Pisoni (2004) on dialect exposure and identification accuracy.

Critically, the trill was NOT significant in quitomod (LRT = 0.301,
p = 0.583) but IS highly significant in lojamod (LRT = 21.78,
p = 3.05e-06). The trill does not push listeners toward guessing Quito —
it helps them correctly identify Loja. The trill is a Loja-specific
acoustic cue, not a generic highland prestige cue.

lojamod_int: guessed_loja ~ trill * Region + status
              + (1|RespondentID) + (1|speakerID)

drop1() results:
status: LRT = 14.4889, p = 0.000141 ***
trill:Region: LRT = 7.0472, p = 0.070 (marginal)

The trill by Region interaction is marginally significant overall (p = 0.070),
driven by trill:RegionCuenca (estimate = 0.7501, z = 2.073, p = 0.038).
Cuenca listeners show a stronger trill effect on Loja attribution than
Coast listeners: when they hear a trill, they are more likely to identify
the speaker as Lojano. This is notable because Cuenca is a neighboring
highland city whose own variety uses assibilation — Cuencano listeners may
be most sensitive to the trill as a distinctively Lojano feature precisely
because it contrasts with their own variety.

Loja listeners show a positive trend (trill:RegionLoja p = 0.119) that does
not reach significance, likely because the main RegionLoja effect is already
very strong (p = 0.000232) — Loja listeners are more accurate overall
regardless of trill condition. Quito listeners show no differential trill
effect (p = 0.880).


SECTION 7: ANSWER TO THE CORE RESEARCH QUESTION

Lojano and non-Lojano listeners do NOT differ in their attitudinal responses
to the trill. The effects of trill on status, niceness, and masculinity are
uniform across all four listener regions — no significant trill by Region
interactions emerged in statusmod_int, nicemod_int, or mascmod_int. The
prestige indexing of the trill is a shared sociolinguistic evaluation across
Ecuadorian listener groups.

Where regional identity DOES matter is in origin attribution. Loja listeners
are more accurate overall in identifying Lojano speakers (in-group advantage,
OR = 2.584). Cuenca listeners show the strongest differential sensitivity to
the trill as a Loja-specific cue (trill:RegionCuenca p = 0.038), likely
because their own assibilating variety makes the trill maximally contrastive.

The trill's social meaning (prestige) is shared; its geographic meaning
(Loja) is more accessible to those with regional familiarity, and most
contrastively salient to listeners whose own variety does not include it.


LIMITATIONS

Only 4 speakers were used (2 trilled, 2 assibilated per gender), resulting
in singular fit warnings in glmer models and near-zero speakerID variance
in trillmod1 and lojamod_int. This is consistent with García (2019), who
excluded speaker as a random effect for the same reason, but it limits
speaker-level generalizability.

The cross-sectional survey design does not allow causal direction between
trill perception and status attribution to be established. All speakers are
from Loja, so findings are specific to the Lojano trill and assibilation
contrast and may not generalize to Quiteño or Cuencano varieties.
predictedOrigin reflects listener guesses only — no ground truth about
speaker origin was available in the dataset. The regional listener sample
is unbalanced, with Loja overrepresented relative to other regions.